Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Montague","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from either Montaigu-le-bois (Manche) or Montaigu (Manche, Aisne), named with Old French <i>mont</i> ‘hill’ + <i>agu</i> ‘pointed’ (from Latin <i>acutus</i>). Drogo de Montagud was a companion of William the Conqueror and founder of the <b>Montagu(e)</b> family, among whom the personal name <i>Drogo</i> was revived in the 19th century. Another family of the name <b>Monatgu</b> have held the titles of Duke of Montagu, Earl of Sandwich, Earl and Duke of Manchester, Earl of Halifax, and Earl of Beaulieu, and.","Irish: adopted as equivalent of Gaelic <b>Mac Taidhg</b> (see   McTigue  )."],"variants":[{"name":"McTigue","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Taidhg</b>, ‘son of <i>Tadhg</i>’, a personal name originally meaning ‘poet’ or ‘philosopher’. Compare   McCaig  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice de Montague was born in 1120, in Shepton Montague, Somerset, England, her father, Sir William de Montague II, was 26 and her mother, Lady William, was 26. She had at least 1 daughter with Richard de Somerset. She died on 7 June 1167, in Montacute, Somerset, England, at the age of 47, and was buried in Montacute, Somerset, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1120–7 June 1167":"1120–7. juuni 1167","1120–1167":"1120–1167","1127–Male":"1127–Surnud","1116–Male":"1116–Surnud","1161–1218":"1161–1218","1095–1156":"1095–1156","1095–Female":"1095–Surnud","1116":"1116","1127":"1127","7 June 1167":"7. juuni 1167","1156":"1156","1167":"1167","1120":"1120","after 7 June 1167":"pärast 7. juunit 1167","1161":"1161","1095":"1095","1218":"1218","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Bishopstone, Montacute, Somerset, England":"Montacute, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shepton Montague, Somerset, England":"Shepton Montague, Somerset, England","Bishopstone, Sussex, England":"Bishopstone, Sussex, England"},"fi":{"1120–7 June 1167":"1120–7. kesäkuuta 1167","1120–1167":"1120–1167","1127–Male":"1127–Kuollut","1116–Male":"1116–Kuollut","1161–1218":"1161–1218","1095–1156":"1095–1156","1095–Female":"1095–Kuollut","1116":"1116","1127":"1127","7 June 1167":"7. kesäkuuta 1167","1156":"1156","1167":"1167","1120":"1120","after 7 June 1167":"7. kesäkuuta 1167 jälkeen","1161":"1161","1095":"1095","1218":"1218","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Bishopstone, Montacute, Somerset, England":"Montacute, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Shepton Montague, Somerset, England":"Shepton Montague, Somerset, Engl